ent/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=375,250 375w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=640,427 640w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=768,512 768w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 767px) 96vw, (max-width: 1280px) 60vw, (max-width: 1536px) 46vw, 710px" data-lazy-src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img data-lazy-fallback="1" width="1024" height="683" src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-170256" sizes="(max-width: 767px) 96vw, (max-width: 1280px) 60vw, (max-width: 1536px) 46vw, 710px" srcset="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg 1024w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=20,12 20w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=375,250 375w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=640,427 640w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/GettyImages-179421367.jpg?resize=768,512 768w" /></noscript><div class="img-caption"><figcaption>A hot air balloon emblazoned with the Turkish flag sailing past some fairy chimneys, a rock formation typical for Cappadocia in central Turkey and one of its main tourist attractions. Another are its ancient underground cities, of which Derinkuyu is the largest.
(<a href="https://www.gettyimages.dk/detail/news-photo/turkis-flagged-hot-air-balloon-the-earth-pillars-on-august-news-photo/179421367?adppopup=true">Credit</a>: Murat Asil / Anadolu Agency / Getty Images)</figcaption></div></figure><p class="has-drop-cap">We live cheek by jowl with undiscovered worlds. Sometimes the barriers that separate us are thick, sometimes they&rsquo;re thin, and sometimes they&rsquo;re breached. That&rsquo;s when a wardrobe turns into a portal to Narnia, a rabbit hole leads to Wonderland, and a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABpeLNCuE3w" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Raquel Welch poster</a> is all that separates a prison cell from the tunnel to freedom.</p><h2 id="h-a-fateful-swing-of-the-hammer">A fateful swing of the hammer</h2><p class="">Those are all fictional examples. But in 1963, that barrier was breached for real. Taking a sledgehammer to a wall in his basement, a man in the Turkish town of Derinkuyu got more home improvement than he bargained for. Behind the wall, he found a tunnel. And that led to more tunnels, eventually connecting a multitude of halls and chambers. It was a huge underground complex, abandoned by its inhabitants and undiscovered until that fateful swing of the hammer.</p><div x-data="{isEmpty: true, slotName: 'bt_content1'}" x-intersect.once.margin.250px="renderSlot()" x-on:ftadslotrendered.window="slotRendered($event)"><div class="advertising advertising--inline" x-cloak="" x-show="!isEmpty" x-transition="" id="bt_content1"></div></div><p class="">The anonymous Turk &mdash; no report mentions his name &mdash; had found a vast subterranean city, up to 18 stories and 280 feet (76 m) deep and large enough to house 20,000 people. Who built it, and why? When was it abandoned, and by whom? History and geology provide some answers.</p><h2>Fantastically craggy Cappadocia</h2><p class="">Geology first. Derinkuyu is located in Cappadocia, a region in the Turkish heartland famed for the fantastic cragginess of its landscape, which is dotted with so-called fairy chimneys. Those tall stone towers are the result of the erosion of a rock type known as <em>tuff</em>. Created out of volcanic ash and covering much of the region, that stone, despite its name, is not so tough.</p><?xml encoding="utf-8" ?><figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img width="1024" height="768" src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg" alt="derinkuyu" class="wp-image-170261 jetpack-lazy-image" data-lazy-srcset="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg 1024w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?resize=375,281 375w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?resize=640,480 640w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?resize=768,576 768w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 767px) 96vw, (max-width: 1280px) 60vw, (max-width: 1536px) 46vw, 710px" data-lazy-src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img data-lazy-fallback="1" loading="lazy" width="1024" height="768" src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg" alt="derinkuyu" class="wp-image-170261" sizes="(max-width: 767px) 96vw, (max-width: 1280px) 60vw, (max-width: 1536px) 46vw, 710px" srcset="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg 1024w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?resize=375,281 375w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?resize=640,480 640w, https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/03/interior-view.jpeg?resize=768,576 768w" /></noscript><div class="img-caption"><figcaption>Well-lit interior view of the otherwise dark and gloomy underground city of Derinkuyu. (<a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Derinkuyu_Underground_City_9908_Nevit_Enhancer.jpg">Credit</a>: Nevit Dilmen / Wikimedia Commons, <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/deed.en">CC BY-SA 3.0</a>)</figcaption></div></figure><p class="">Taking a cue from the wind and rain, the locals for millennia have dug their own holes in the soft stone for underground dwellings, storage rooms, temples, and refuges. Cappadocia numbers hundreds of subterranean dwellings, with about 40 consisting of at least two levels. None is as large, or by now as famous, as Derinkuyu.</p><h2>Hittites, Phrygians, or early Christians?</h2><p class="">The historical record has little definitive to say about Derinkuyu&rsquo;s origins. Some archaeologists speculate that the oldest part of the complex could have been dug about 2000 BC by the Hittites, the people who dominated the region at that time, or else the Phrygians, around 700 BC. Others claim that local Christians built the city in the first centuries AD. </p><div class="bt-block bt-inline-form bt-inline-form__standard xl:my-0"> <div class="bt-block__inner"> <div class="bt-block__content"> <div class="max-w-[260px]"> <img width="600" height="220" src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/smarter_faster.svg?w=128&amp;h=96&amp;crop=1" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail jetpack-lazy-image" alt="Smarter faster: the Big Think newsletter" data-lazy-src="https://bigthink.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/smarter_faster.svg?w=128&amp;h=96&amp;crop=1&amp;is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"> </div> <div class="font-utility-subtitle-small mt-[10px]"> Subscribe for counterintuitive, surprising, and impactful stories delivered to your inbox every Thursday </div> <div class="mt-[25px] w-2/3 sm:w-full"> <noscript class="ninja-forms-noscript-message"> Notice: JavaScript is required for this content.</noscript><div id="nf-form-10-cont" class="nf-form-cont bt-form-wrapper bt-form-wrapper--short form-tight-multicolumn" aria-